<br>
Both Sony and Microsoft are losing between $100 - $150 per system sold.  Their profit margin is in the games.  <br>
<br>
I manage a games store and, by God, Halo was the best selling game we had this month.  The Xbox is currently outselling PS2's for us by a factor of 2 to 1.  Four new titles came out for the Xbox within the last week and a half and a veritable tidal wave of games is coming out this Fall.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, we're taking in between 3 - 5 defective PS2's per week, compared to the Xbox, for which I've only seen 10 defective units in total since the machine was released last year.  And before you dredge up those rumors about the Xbox overheating . . . they're bollocks.  Better to ask yourselves why that rumor managed to flare up within 24 hours of the Xbox's release, right at the time it was easiest for such a rumor to damage the machine's credibility.  Meanwhile, the myriad problems with the PS2 are mysteriously ignored by gaming magazines and websites who are afraid of angering the Sony behemoth.  EGM finally published a very small piece on this problem about two or three months ago, but most of the game platform magazines are still wary of losing any advertising revenue from Sony by going public.<br>
<br>
If you don't believe this, go to your local gaming store and ask them, confidentially, about return rates on PS2's.  You're going to hear shocking numbers, between 20% to 30% especially from the first batch of pre-revision PS2 hardware.  The subsequent revision continues to have about a 10% to 15% defect rate.  The most prominent issues include the player suddenly losing the ability to read DVD discs, or game discs on DVD; the sudden inability to read BLUE discs while DVD discs work just fine; the very rickety CD tray popping out of place on the gears by a tooth and no longer opening or closing properly; and the laser lens head popping out of place when the machine is in its vertical position -- as it is SUPPOSEDLY able to be placed -- and physically hitting the surface of the disc, causing heavy concentric damage to the disc and rendering it unplayable.<br>
<br>
Look, those of you who bought PS2's are just as much in dutch to Sony -- a monumental corporation, that at heart doesn't give a real rat's ass about you -- as anyone who purchases a Microsoft product.  Both companies are out to make money.  At least the Xbox is a much more reliable piece of hardware, hands-down. <p><BR>
